time arguments weren't applied correctly. I need to decide on an advisory preparation with agent guidance to address the new version's runtime arguments for Netty on Java 25 to avoid access or reflection failures.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring action guidance**\\n\\nI’m wondering if we should proceed with action or simply provide guidance. The recommendation is to include environment variables and system properties in the agent guidance, so I think that might lead to an action of advisory preparation if there's any guidance available. I need to note the risks related to adding a native classifier dependency, as it may need specific kernel support and actually accessing io_uring. Existing tests seem to ensure certain functionalities without Docker, but if true roundtrips are necessary, a native classifier and memlock would be essential. I’m questioning if meaningful coverage is actually reachable this way, too.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Checking metadata for coverage**\\n\\nIt looks like the metadata does include resource configurations for native libraries, but if there's no native JAR, then the resource metadata might not be fully utilized. That could lead to stats showing 100% calls with 0 activity, which seems off. For GRM, it might mean that dynamic access coverage is based on missing registrations instead of actual code coverage. I should consider how to address this discrepancy and ensure that the tests are reflective of the true library functionality.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "{\n  \"action\": \"advisory_preparation\",\n  \"summary\": \"No extra Maven dependency or Docker image is required for the classes artifact, but Java 25 native-image runs need Netty unsafe/reflection system properties before the existing meaningful tests can run.\",\n  \"deterministic_setup\": [],\n  \"agent_guidance\": \"For nativeTest/native-image execution of io.netty:netty-transport-classes-io_uring:4.2.4.Final, set runtime system properties `-Dsun.misc.unsafe.memory.access=allow` and `-Dio.netty.tryReflectionSetAccessible=true`. The existing 4.2.3 test scaffold already does this only for `4.2.3.Final`; extend that condition or make it apply to the tested 4.2.x version. Do not require the native io_uring classifier just to get coverage: the target artifact is the Java-side `classes` artifact, and tests can exercise the availability/unavailability contract when the native library is absent.\",\n  \"risks\": [\n    \"Full io_uring transport round-trip tests require the platform classifier artifact such as `io.netty:netty-transport-native-io_uring:<version>:linux-x86_64`, a supported Linux kernel, and sufficient memlock limits; adding that would change test assumptions and may make CI environment-dependent.\",\n    \"If the system properties are only applied to JVM tests and not nativeTest runtime arguments, local Gradle verification may pass while native-image run still fails.\"\n  ]\n}", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0988f49ca163202f016a3e58ec1a6c81948147420ac4fd17ba\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 660, "output": 1261, "cacheRead": 37888, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 39809, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp": 1782470874651, "responseId": "resp_0988f49ca163202f016a3e58db380c81948afb9d689874310d"}, "toolResults": []}
